  "summary": "Comprehensive code review of sentiment scoring and ranking modules.\n\nReviewed radar/ranking/filters.py (SentimentFilter) and radar/ranking/scorer.py for scoring accuracy, normalization logic, and edge cases. All 21 unit tests passing.\n\nKey Findings:\n1. HIGH: Unbounded sentiment amplification in _sentiment_factor() - sentiment factor uses 1.0 + abs(raw) without clamping, can reach 2.0x amplification for extreme sentiment. Recommend adding explicit bounds [1.0, 2.0] and None validation.\n\n2. MEDIUM: Sentiment score mutation on all posts (not just passing) - SentimentFilter.apply() computes and stores sentiment on ALL posts even those failing threshold, creating inconsistent state if pipeline changes. Document as side effect.\n\n3. MEDIUM: Log-normalization edge case - _log10_norm() doesn't validate that input value >= 0. log10(value+1) with negative value produces negative output before clamping. Add explicit non-negative enforcement.\n\n4. LOW: Dead code _log1p_norm() - defined but never called, should be removed or documented.\n\n5. LOW: Inefficient maintainer boost recount - re-instantiates MaintainerContextFilter for every post, recomputing signal count already done in filter layer. Cache on RawPost model.\n\n6. LOW: Float precision at threshold -0.05 - potential boundary rounding issues, document expected behavior.\n\n7. LOW: No text length bounds - _combined_score() processes arbitrary text size, no documented limits for VADER/TextBlob.\n\nStrengths: Clean separation of concerns, appropriate log-normalization, comprehensive test coverage, graceful library handling.\n\nWeaknesses: Sentiment factor lacks defensive bounds, side-effects undocumented, dead code present, inefficient recomputation.\n\nConclusion: System is functionally correct and produces reasonable ranking order. Normalization robustness should be improved before scaling to larger batches. Created ANALYSIS-TASK-005.md with detailed recommendations and code examples.",
